rows.title: Worm CYOA
rows.titleText:
Two beings spiral through the void, past stars, and worlds. They dance through realities, shifting through other times, other dimensions. Countless facets that fuse, part, and shift as they journey. Approaching a world they shatter. Shards falling into millions of alternate worlds to root. Reaching out across the boundaries of dimensions they bond, empowering those they find. Those at their lowest. People who will fight, suffer, and strive, and in doing so drive the entities own evolution. 

But unlike the cycles before this something has gone wrong. A single mistake leads to the death of one of these entities. Only it's shards remaining as it's mate is left behind, shocked and insensiate in it's mourning. As things stand now the worlds within the reach of these beings are now set on a painful and destructive course that will reap untold costs in human lives and suffering. 

But you are going to be given a chance to change that. You are going to Earth Bet, the center of these events, and with power to potentially avert the disaster that is swiftly approaching. Make your choices below, but no matter what you choose remember one thing. Conflict is inevitable.

rows.title: Difficulty
rows.titleText:
To begin, choose the difficulty of your adventures.

Notes: Anything left unsaid is effectively left up to your imagination. If all else fails assume that options work the way you wish them to. If you have not read Worm then I suggest either looking up a quick summary or simply treating this as a generic superhero CYOA and deciphering what you can about the setting from the choices. As a special note the Wormverse is a vast if technically finite universe. Assume certain boundaries separare it from the rest of an infinite universe filled with all possibilities. Your home earth is past these, and therefore safe from being reached by the Wormverse's threats unless you specifically bring them there with your powers.

objects.title: World Breaker
objects.text: All of your powers start out twice as strong. You have no special ability to avoid danger, but you also have little need to fear it.

objects.title: Easy
objects.text: Danger seems to avoid you unless you go looking for it.

objects.title: Standard
objects.text: What danger and conflict you encounter depends on your actions and the whims of chance.

objects.title: Hard
objects.text: You will find yourself dragged into major conflicts more often than not. Avoiding this will be hard and require significant effort.

objects.title: Skitter
objects.text: Powers start out half as strong, or are limited in some other significant fashion. You must take complications to earn points.

rows.title: Method of Arrival
rows.titleText: Choose the nature of your entry into this world.

objects.title: Self Insert
objects.text: You are dropped off into Brockton Bay on April 8th, 2011. Taylor is currently trying to avoid her tormentors and in a few short days will be taking to the streets for the first time. You are able to pick a set of clothes that you will own to take with you, and you are given a scant hundred bucks in your pocket. Beyond this, however, you will have to make your own way. You are alone, with no experience in this world, and nothing that you haven't already purchased with points. However you are a completely unknown factor to the people here, giving you a perfect opportunity to blindside the established players and status-quo.

objects.title: Reincarnation
objects.text: In what feels like the span of a moment you are born into Earth Bet and live out a life up until the age of your choosing, at which point you regain your memories and begin to control your actions normally. The circumstances of this life are entirely under your control, including gender, appearance, race, and who your family is. You can't make major changes to the setting as a part of this, although minor changes keeping with your life and presence are fine. From what point you had your powers and perks is up to you, and depending on what you have purchase may give you more leeway in effecting the setting. At the latest your life can run up until the start of the canon story, the same time that you would have arrived as a Self Insert, beyond this you will have to go about your adventure normally. You retain all the skill and experiences of your new life, ensuring you are familiar with Earth Bet and the various little differences that diverge it from our Earth. Note that you are specifically able to modify your personality to your wishes. Beyond this all new memories and experiences are integrated flawlessly and seamlessly.

objects.title: Endbringer
objects.text:
You awaken not to a strange street or a new life, but to an unfurling of alien senses and thoughts. While you have not lost your memories, sense of self, of free will, you are now an Endbringer, a monster of terrifying power and untold destructive might. You choose your new form, which may range anywhere from ten to one thousand feet in height. It may appear human-like, but not fully so. Your flesh is incredibly strong, even at its frailest being enough to compare to the durability of a strong Brute class parahuman. It is impossibly dense, growing exponentially more so the deeper it goes, warping space to render itself more compact then possible for any natural material. If you are large, expect only the strongest parahumans to give you more than flesh wounds. You also regenerate, with denser flesh restoring itself faster. A core somewhere within your body is your only organ or weakness, and only it being completely annihilated will result in your death. Beyond that you are immune to pain, debilitation, physical needs, and permanent injury, able to fight at full effectiveness even when reduced to nothing but your core and skeleton. 

All purchased powers are an order of magnitude stronger and the nature of your alien senses will be determined by them. You cannot take companions other then friends, and can only take complications specifically meant for your origin. The entire world will perceive you as one of it's greatest threats, and the opposition brought against you will be intense and merciless. However before the sheer raw power you now lay claim to it is unlikely to prevail. Even the mightiest of parahumans is a gnat before a hurricane in the face of your wrath. You begin dormant, and may choose exactly at what time and place you emerge.

rows.title: Powers
rows.titleText:
Earth Bet is home to heroes and villains, all of whom wield superhuman powers in the name of their ideals, ambitions, or merely to survive. The powers you are about to gain do not come from an entity's shards and as such are not subject to the same limits, regardless of any similarities. Tinkers can mass produce their work easily if they get the resources, Thinkers can read the futures of the entities just as easily as that of anyone else, and the Manton Effect is no limit to you. Your powers will grow over time in response to stress and conflict as the experience pushes them to improve, and with effort you may even stretch your powers to function in new and creative ways that are beyond their original beginnings. You may buy as many as you wish so long as you can afford it. Powers purchase integrate and function together seamlessly, and you never have to worry about their use having negative side effects. All powers and their aspects may be toggled on and off at will.

Note: Due to opinion being overwhelmingly in favor of more power rather than less, and how dangerous the threats facing the Wormverse are, powers are much more powerful then other parahumans. Remember that the remaining entity is still out there, and it can casually destroy planets. Combined with meta knowledge these powers should be enough to turn a desperate slog into a decent chance for victory, but there is a major difference of knowing what to do and pulling it off. If you'd rather be weaker then choose the appropriate difficulty and complications.

objects.title: Alexandria
objects.text: You are completely and absolutely invulnerable and immune to harm. No effect or force can negatively effect you physically, regardless of it's nature. This extends even to the functions of your own body, meaning that you never tire, require no sustenance (air included), and even negative mental effects are limited to the point that you don't have to worry about stress doing permanent mental harm. Even sleep is just for pleasure of relaxation rather than a need to refresh yourself. You have almost limitless amounts of strength and can fly and move at hyper sonic speeds, with perfect maneuverability and reaction time to match. You can see and hear at extreme distances, even if doing so should otherwise be impossible. Your mind is enhanced just like your body, skyrocketing your mental capabilities to superhuman levels, with an absolutely perfect memory. The field that pervades your body providing these abilities also extends itself to the things you are touching, letting you ignore the effects of physics when you apply your strength and speed. You have more leverage then should be possible when you grab something, exert immense force with minor motions, large objects don't collapse under their own weight, and catching or carrying people at extreme speeds won't harm them. You are an unstoppable force and an immovable object.

objects.title: Legend
objects.text: Your very being is entwined with energy on fundamental levels. You can fire blasts of light whose properties and effects are within your control. Forking or homing lasers, freeze beams, disintegrating spheres that orbit around you in a pattern. All of these and more are within your capabilities. At their strongest a single one of these can vaporize a mountain, and your rate of fire is measured in millions of blasts per second. Coordinating and managing such barrages is trivial for you. You are also able to fly, reaching the speed of light in an instant, and doubling every second you spend moving in a straight line. You do not experience relativistic time dilation or other effects of this flight unless you wish to. Secondary mental powers also render you immune to negative mental effects of isolation, boredom, and extended periods of time, letting you travel between galaxies if you so wished. You are able to switch back and forth between a breaker state that removes all physical needs, and quickly restores you to perfect physical condition. In this state most attacks are simply absorbed, with only the strongest able to put you down before the damage is gone. Your vision is perfect, encompasses the entire electromagnetic spectrum, and no longer degrades with distance. It is even able to see through solid objects and other obstructions.

objects.title: Eidolon
objects.text: The deciding factor of any parahuman struggle is the nature of the powers involved. Fortunately you have access to all of them. You have five slots, each of which can contain any power you wish, and may be swapped out at will. If you do not direct them consciously then your power will automatically provide abilities that aid you in surviving and achieving your goals, adapting to whatever circumstances you are facing. It's ability to predict your needs and wants is absolutely preternatural, the powers it chooses are often perfect for changes in the situation that haven't happened yet. Only the most extraordinary or intense of circumstances could force it to swap out a slot more then once every few minutes. You have a perfect understanding of all of these powers, down to the tiniest nuance and quirk. This means you will never be confused, disoriented, or even slowed down from a switch, and know how to use them perfectly. The strength of these is capped at a certain point, but even at their weakest they never fall beneath an 8 on the PRT scale, with powers rated 9-10 being the norm. Considering that powers of this level are enough to require redrawing maps this should hardly be a problem for you.

objects.title: Emperor of Man
objects.text:
Within you blooms unparalleled psychic might and impossibly vast vistas of knowledge. Any knowledge or skill that was possessed by a human being from the 40k universe at any point in time is granted to you, and all at superhuman levels of proficiency. Your physical and mental abilities skyrocket as well, leaving you able to go toe to toe with Brutes and Thinkers simply from raw prowess. Your psyker abilities are the equal of the Emperor's at his peak, with perfect control and understanding. The Warp does not exist here, meaning you are immune to the perils that normally plague psykers. You know how to induce these abilities in others, and train them in their use. Combined with your mastery of all human technology you have all the knowledge to forge an empire greater and vaster than anything possible in the original lore. First things first. You'll need warriors to face the dangers of this world beside you. Genetic technologies and treatments float to the forefront of your mind, almost like they are eager to raise your first legions.

-Your mastery of humanities' technology explicitly extends to things that the Imperium did not understand, or had long forgotten about. You are the equal of any Tinker when it comes to applying this knowledge.

-If you wish, your body becomes that of the Emperor as well. Don't expect to blend into a crow or have much of a secret identity. Not that you should conceal your unbound majesty, of course.

-Daemons are not a thing, but you could theoretically create psychic entities. I'm sure that won't go badly in any way.

-Games Workshop will file a lawsuit against you for being the Emperor. Even if in your glorious magnanimity you spare them despite this heresy, they will keep trying.

objects.title: Kaleidoscope
objects.text: You are attuned to not only the fabric of space and time, but the very essence of the multiverse itself. All worlds, timelines, and possibilities are now within reach of your new senses, and you find yourself able to manipulate them to your will, and even travel between them. What you can accomplish with this is limited only to your creativity, imagination, and experience. Drawing in alternate versions of people to fight under your control, copying powers from alternate selves or fictional characters, fixing a destroyed neighborhood by overlapping a pristine version on it. These and any imaginable manipulation of space and time (time travel included) are within your reach, and it isn't limited to the Wormverse. The entirety of the infinity is at your fingertips. If you wanted to you could just walk on home right now and leave Earth Bet to its fate. But where is the fun in that.

objects.title: Inspired Inventor
objects.text: You are the world's first Tinker 12. Each day you have FIVE charges which can be spent to improve your tinker abilities within a specific area or theme. A single charge would make you a good Tinker within an area, roughly a Tinker 4 or 5. Each additional charge after this doubles your abilities (around a two point bump in rating), with no limits to how many times you can spend a charge on a certain area. As a Tinker you have superhuman scientific knowledge, understanding, and skill at applying it, able to make or do things that modern science would consider impossible within your theme. Spend a charge on Augmentation and start crafting cybernetics out of scrap. Spend some on medicine and cure cancer in an hour. Should your different themes overlap, then they stack, building off of each other and integrating perfectly. All fields of knowledge are viable for this. Spending charges on martial arts would let you design and teach unbelievable fighting styles, and a political science Tinker could design forms of government that function better than anything we have today. As long as you have time and resources, there isn't anything you couldn't do.

objects.title: Psychokinetic
objects.text: With nothing but your will alone, you are capable of shaping the physical world. Moving objects, generating and manipulating all forms of energy or matter, or even creating psychic constructs. The world is a vast ocean of vibration, matter, and energy to your senses, and all it takes is a thought to send it moving according to your wishes. Complex systems such as biology and technology will require a great deal of practice before you can reliably work with them the same way you would matter and energy, with other powers here being far better at doing so and developing faster. But when it comes to the sheer breadth and raw power to control the physical world, you are peerless. The Endbringer Behemoth's Dynakinesis is the only other power the world has seen that could compare. It would be wise to show caution when using your abilities. It would not be difficult for you to level cities and leave them uninhabitable for centuries.

objects.title: Power Manipulation
objects.text: Some of the rarest and most values parahumans are those who can effect the powers of others. People who nullify allow enemy parahumans to be subdued as easily as an unpowered human being, while those who boost others' powers give their allies a much needed edge over the opposition. Some even have the ability to copy or steal powers temporarily. You can do all of this and more, and only your personal desires can stop such effects from being permanent. You can nullify, enhance, modify, copy, and even steal the powers of others (whether this takes the shard along with them is up to you). Transferring powers from one person to another is trivial, even stacking multiple into a single target. You also have FIVE charges a day which let you create shardless powers like yours, whose nature are fully under your control. A single charge can result in a power that would be rated around a 4 or 5, with more charges increasing its power, versatility, pushing or removing limits, and adding more functions. You can manipulate and sense created powers regardless of the location of anyone you have given them to. You also have an ability to sense parahumans and powers within a large area. Created powers are yours until you transfer them to someone else. Charges can also be spent to boost any of YOUR powers, including others bought here. Changes can be reversed at will, and you can deconstruct powers you have created, but you do not recover any charges from doing so.

objects.title: Shaper
objects.text: You are a master of biology and life in all its forms and functions. You are capable of complete control and manipulation of all organic material within a massive area, and also sense and understand every detail about it down to the atomic level. Your power is able to generate biomass to fuel its uses, meaning you are not limited to whatever material is on hand. Shifting the nature and function of biomass takes only a thought, with it automatically conforming to what you desire and what you will it to be and do. This power extends to your own body as well. You and special creatures you design can function as the nexuses of a hive mind. This allows you to function consciously even if you lose your entire nervous system, and as long as some organisms and biomass remain a part of this, you are capable of reassembling yourself. If Panacea, Nilbog, Kerrigan, or Alex Mercer could do it, then you can do it better and faster. Nilbog has left the world in fear of powers the likes of this. Should the full scope of your abilities become apparent, you will quickly be labeled an S-Class threat of global nature. To be honest, they wouldn't be entirely wrong in that assessment. The only limit to the range of your hive mind is that organisms must be within reach of a nexus. Otherwise distance is meaningless. You are incapable of being severed from it and always retain absolute control.

rows.title: Companions
rows.titleText: No man is an island. The world is dangerous, and those who go it alone more often than not perish. For all the power that you now have there is no substitute for true friends. If you chose Self Insert then you will run into any companions you buy within your first week or two in Earth Bet, and find yourself natural allies and comrades. Reincarnated choose how they know their companions, and what the nature of their relationship is. Your bonds will be strong enough that they will stand with you through anything, fight by your side, and brave any danger to come to your aid. Regardless of whether you choose to be a hero or a villain, they'll be right there with you.

objects.title: The Highwayman and the Butterfly
objects.text: This brother and sister duo have survived by hitting gangs and making off with their hard earned cash, moving on the a new city when the heat gets to be too much. Both of them are as strong, tough, and agile as spiderman on his best day, with a similar danger sense to boot. Mark is also superhumanly skilled in any form of combat imaginable, while Violet is perfectly silent and has thinker abilities that let her know exactly how to avoid detection. Despite technically being villains, they are rather kind and idealistic, seeing the best in people and often going out of their way to help those in need. Optimistic, friendly, and resourceful beyond all belief. You couldn't ask for better friends, but they won't stomach cruelty or unwarranted violence. Note that hospitalizing villains who prey on and harm innocent people or their friends falls under warranted violence in their opinion.

objects.title: The Steel Demons
objects.text: Twin sisters who have been dodging attempts to force them into one gang or another for a long time. They have only had each other to rely on for as long as they can remember. Someone else having their back is an experience that they aren't really used to. Life has made them a bit ruthless, pragmatic, and suspicious, but they will quickly warm up to you. Kim's specialty is personal equipment, anything that would be carried, worn, attached to, or used by a single person. Nagase's is similar, instead being for vehicles, mechs, and everything that relates to them. Getting them a proper workshop and supplying them with materials could take work but could let them equip an army. For some reason they don't seem to have any problem mass producing their tech, almost like their powers were meant to create a military infrastructure. Unless they specifically design something as such even maintenance and repair seems easy enough for anybody to be able to do it.

objects.title: The Renegades
objects.text:
These three have been involved in nearly every form of villany and parahuman combat imaginable. They have fought, stole, destroyed, and killed ever since gaining their powers. How you met them isn't important. They are tired of working for every two bit gang and villain, running all over the country, never able to settle down or know a moment's peace. Working for you is their chance to do something bigger than surviving. They are the perfect enforcers and heavy hitters, able to work together flawlessly to get the job done. Alone each of them is an extremely experienced and skilled combatant that can be driven off but rarely defeated. Together they are an unstoppable force who can shred entire groups of parahumans. While they have nothing against returning to hero work, their history would make that an uphill battle at the very best. Their loyalty is assured, and they'll follow whatever path you lead them down gladly. All they ask in return is that you make it mean something.

Riot: Riot generates clouds of gas that he can use to sense anything within it's area. These can be made of countless different kinds of gases, some that are harmless, some irritating, others horrifyingly lethal. He can shift their nature and composition with a thought, and detonate them in devastating explosions or concussive blasts. His mastery of parahuman tactics and strategy is peerless, turning hopeless situations into resounding victories. His only weakness is that his physical capabilities are technically human. Pity the poor bastards who think that means he is easy to take down.

Frost: A cryokinetic that can generate and manipulate incredibly dense ice that is the next best thing to unbreakable. Immune to cold and able to shift his own body into this ice to become stronger, tougher, regenerate, and even teleport through ice he has created. In raw parahuman power he is the strongest of the three. Combat wise he is an unbreakable bastion, his opponents more likely to break themselves then his defenses. Only the strongest Blasters and Brutes will be able to directly overpower him, and doing so only turns it into a fair fight.

Warlock: An absolute monster even compared to the rest of his team. He has extreme strength, durability, and regeneration. He also creates reddish black flames that can shroud him or disintegrate whatever they strike. He has spent years tearing apart parahumans who everyone thought were unbeatable, those who manager to get away usually crippled and doing whatever necessary to avoid a second encounter. His senses are perfect, and ignore anything that would stop or debilitate them. He can see his targets through walls, track a single thug that passed through a busy street weeks ago by scent, and pinpoint attackers by the sound of their heartbeat. Along with a mastery of stealth his fights have more in common with horror flicks than battles. The deadliest of the three by far.

objects.title: The Bodyguards
objects.text: These two aren't really capes, instead working as bodyguards for anybody with a need for protection. They have a reputation for being the best in the business, without a single client having been kidnapped, killed, or seriously injured. James is a Thinker, his power giving him a perfect analysis and awareness of a situation, and letting him apply his skills perfectly to resolve danger and threats. His shots never miss, small movements leave gunfire and attacks veering past harmlessly, and nullifying threats to his allies is more reflex than conscious action. Micheal is able to perfectly analyze materials, structures, and objects, knowing everything about them down to their atomic structure. He is able to assemble anything he's analyzed from matter, even tinker tech being viable if he's had a moment to study it. His power extends slightly to living beings, letting him diagnose a person's condition, and know exactly where to hit his opponents to keep them down. They strike up a camaraderie with you, and decide that tagging along with you is more fun than their old work. They'll wind up saving you and your allies lives before you even know they are in danger on a routine basis.

objects.title: The Freaks (Slither, Crag, Chitin)
objects.text: These three Case-53s are some of the first to ever appear. Unfortunately unlike most they are completely inhuman, unable to interact in normal human society at all. They've spent a long time surviving the streets and fighting off every villain who wants to take a shot at them or hero who considers them criminals. After you meet them and earn their trust they attach themselves to you due to being one of the few people who was kind to them. The isolation and loneliness they have gone through leaves them willing to go to any lengths to keep you safe. Fighting with a feral and horrific zeal if it means protecting their newfound friends and allies. All of them are powerful Brute class parahumans, their monstrous forms insanely powerful. They recover from all but the most extreme damage in minutes, and as long as they are not killed are back to peak shape within an hour. Communicating is a bit difficult, with Chitin's rasping voice being the only form of speech any of them can manage.

objects.title: Friend Inserts
objects.text:
What's the point of getting superpowers and saving the world if you can't do it with your friends? Choose up to 5 friends from your real life to come with you. They each get 1/3rd of your final points to spend, they share your origin and difficulty modifications. There isn't any special guarantee that your friendship will survive the trials ahead, and rest assured Earth Bet will test just how strong your bonds are. Neither is there a promise that you will all make it out alive and well. But should you stay together you will be an extremely powerful group of parahumans, able to go toe to toe with nearly anyone.

- Self Insert: You and your friends are dropped into exactly the same spot.

- Reincarnation: You and your friends know what life was chosen by each other, meaning you have no need to search for one another.

- Endbringer: Your friends make the choices of their form and when to emerge as normal. You are aware of each others choices and share a mental bond that lets you all communicate regardless of distance or location. Endbringers operate alone, so expect a lot of attention and panic if you all fight and work together.

- Your friends share complications you choose, and points from these are added to your pool before being divided to determine your friends' points. Friends can purchase powers and perks only.

rows.title: Perks
rows.titleText: Each perk may be bought once unless otherwise specified.

objects.title: Blank
objects.text: Knowledge is power, and that means that an opponent who knows what your every move will be is an unbelievable threat. By taking this you are completely immune to being perceived by Thinker abilities. Your future and past cannot be observed, clairvoyants cannot detect you, and even danger senses cannot warn their users of an incoming attack from you. This is pervading enough that you cannot even be perceived by noticing blind spots in their sight, such powers simply acting as if you didn't exist. This applies only to uses of powers that are hostile to you. Other thinker abilities that do not rely on directly perceiving you with the power itself are unaffected. Enhanced senses pick you up just as easily, Tattletale can still read you like an open book, and Coil is still able to perceive you in his split timelines.

objects.title: Shattered Limiter
objects.text: The factors that kept your powers growth and ability in check are completely done away with. At a base this doubles the number of slots and charges you have available. Your power growth skyrockets, with your power doubling in strength every year if you do nothing but live a normal life. Actually fighting on a regular basis drops this down to half a year. Each such interval also increases the number of slots and charges your power provides by one. Your powers refuse to be kept in check, rendering you immune to trumps who would try to effect your abilities.

objects.title: Invictus
objects.text: Your will is absolute, boundless, and unbreakable. By taking this factors such as distress, suffering, and difficulty mean nothing to you. You are capable of undergoing any disaster without batting an eye, ignoring any amount of pain, remaining mentally untouched by even the most terrible events, and even the most fearsome odds will not give you pause. Abilities that would effect your mind or control you are useless, you shrugging these off as being nothing more than an irritant. You will never break, never bow, and even come a thousand apocalypses you will stand as tall and resolute as ever. Being torn in half, locked into a time loop of endless agony for thousands of years, or facing the most hopeless odds are nothing to you.

objects.title: Inspiration
objects.text: Something about you reaches directly into the hearts and souls of others. Even if you don't lead them, just your presence seems to lift their spirits and restore their hope. You'll find it nearly trivial to recruit others and sway them to your cause. Wherever you go people see you and find new purpose and courage. The broken will rise above their suffering to go on, hopeless defenders will rally to defy the odds, and even the most inhuman of your enemies will be shaken with a sense of terrified awe at your presence. This perk is effectively the same as Invictus, but applying to the people you lead or fight beside. As long as you stand they will never stop fighting, and should you fall your memory will drive them to greatness and heroism that has only existed in the imagination.

objects.title: First Impressions
objects.text: No matter what you do it seems like you're incapable of making a bad impression on others when they encounter you. Even your enemies will find themselves respecting you, seeing you as a worthy opponent. You'll find it trivial to find a place with various factions, and they'll be more than willing to help you out or extend the benefit of the doubt. This isn't permanent, your actions and decisions will influence them as normal, but you are given significantly more leeway than would be extended to anyone else. Expect to become very popular with the media should you so much as give them the time of day.

objects.title: Bottled Superpowers
objects.text: You arrive with a nondescript case that contains ten cauldron-like formulas that are guaranteed to give people top tier powers. You don't get to decide exactly what power each vial will give, but you may choose a general theme for each that is roughly one or two words (Division, Impairment, Conqueror, Extrapolation, etc) which will influence what the possible powers are. There is no risk of mutation or other negative effects from taking these, and you may hand them out to whoever you wish. The powers are shardless like yours. The vials are magically created for you, so you don't have to worry about Cauldron hunting you down to recover their property. Only you have the password to the case, but it can still be stolen from you. If drank by a parahuman they lose their shard and instead gain the powers from the vial. What powers are granted is still influenced by the personality and nature of the drinker.

objects.title: Secret Lair
objects.text: Instead of being dropped into an back street you arrive in a very well hidden and secured hideout that has all the space you could need, utilities that are fully functional and untraceable, and fully stocked with resources. You may decide the exact nature of the hideout and how large you wish it to be, but you are capped at roughly a large city building in size. Comes with tools and workshop for tinkers, materials included. Enjoy living like a Bond villain.

objects.title: Cloak and Dagger
objects.text: You find it almost trivial to gain contacts, expand networks, plant spies, sabotage, and even assassinate. Espionage in all of its forms is as easy as breathing to you, almost without regard for reasonable limits. While this isn't a power your talent here is great enough that it might as well be. Within days you could have your thumb on the pulse of information throughout the city, with even the most secretive dealing unable to be hidden from you, and the limit to which you can expand are limited only by the trivial effort it requires for you to bother. Not even the most secure and secretive groups would be able to keep you out if you put any effort into learning their secrets.

objects.title: Manpower
objects.text: I don't know how you do it but you are able to find, recruit, and manage competent and loyal minions (or workers, troops, professionals, etc) with almost zero effort. Whether it's lawyers, mercenaries, doctors, or just raw manpower you have no trouble finding people to work for you. This extends to training, even minor effort showing extreme gains. The logistical efforts needed to pay and support them also becoming extremely easy, money seeming to show up whenever you need to sign paychecks, high quality equipment abundant, even political leverage if you need to keep a politician or two loyal to you. Fate itself seems to be opposed to the idea that you would lack for somebody to call on. Only the most extraordinary circumstances could prevent you from having people to rely on, and never for very long.

objects.title: Alternate Continuity
objects.text: By taking this perk the restrictions on the changes you can make to canon in choosing your life are completely removed. Any changes you can imagine are fair game, the only hard rule being the presence of Parahumans, Endbringers, and Entities. Want Earth Bet to fight off the Endbringers with mechs that channel the powers of their pilots? Want the nature of shards to be different, parahumans triggering in a moment of unbridled heroism? Perhaps there are no shards, Parahumans abilities being a natural evolutionary trait of humans who undergo a trigger event, with the entities having arrived here to study them. As long as those three basics are obeyed in some form or another, your wishes are fair game.

objects.title: Additional Core
objects.text: Instead of having a single core, you have multiple. As long as one remains you remain alive, and cores will regenerate within a day of being destroyed. Multiple cores also mean your regeneration in general improves, healing and restoring yourself faster. Should you wish you can even push a core out of your body and leave it somewhere, acting as a seed to regrow yourself should you be destroyed. This perk can be purchased multiple times, granting one additional core per purchase. You may regrow cores you cannot recover, rending their predecessors inert. A seed core will regrow your body within a few days. Powers may speed up this process.

objects.title: Alien Nature
objects.text: Endbringer physiology may appear biological, but when examined closely shows to have more in common with crystal than flesh. This is partially the source of their mighty physical abilities. By taking this perk you are able to completely modify the nature of your body, regardless of how exotic the end result is. Do you wish to be an angelic monster made of pure fractal light, your death requiring the destruction of your ever shining core in complete darkness? How about a living equation who is expressed by the strange warping of the world as you pass through it, only able to be slain if you are unravelled by a mathematical formula that renders you down to zero? You must have some form of "core" with it's complete destruction resulting in your death.

objects.title: Unbound Form
objects.text: Unlike the other Endbringers who have a static form, you are capable of shifting yours to adapt to new experiences and circumstances. With a day of dormancy you can completely reform your body around your core, modifying your Endbringer nature to any other form made possible by your choices. You may end a period of dormancy at any time, such as to defend yourself from attackers. This has no negative effects but does require that you return to dormancy to complete your transformation.

rows.title: Complications
rows.titleText: Complications grant a number of points based on how inconvenient they are.

objects.title: Everything Gets Worse
objects.text: Your adventure isn't bound to some rule that means everything has to go wrong, and there is nothing stopping you from making genuine positive changes. Taking this complication changes that. Fate is going to keep guiding everything to fall apart at the seams. Heroes will die, monsters will get away to reap even more innocent lives, and your victories will be only wrought at the cost of sacrifice. You can still make it here, win even. But it will be a long, hard road filled with sacrifice and pain, and will most likely leave you a broken and shattered wreck.

objects.title: Marked
objects.text: Within your first week here you wind up accidentally stepping on someone's toes. This is always a significant faction within the area, such as the Empire Eighty Eight. You will have to deal with their attempts to capture or kill you as they try to set an example for the rest of their opposition. This complication pisses off a faction. May be taken three times.

objects.title: Leviathan
objects.text: Leviathan hit Brockton Bay because of Bakuda's bombing spree in the original story. Now his attack will be directed at you. Within a month of you arriving here he will strike, attempting to slay you and do as much damage tot the area as possible. Should you somehow avoid him he hits three different cities in succession, devastating them all in an attempt to draw you out. Facing him will prevent this regardless of the outcome. His goal is to either kill you or reveal your capabilities to the Protectorate and Cauldron.

objects.title: Quarantined
objects.text:
You aren't dropped into Brockton Bay, but Canberra, the site of Simurgh's attacks. This place is sealed off from the rest of the world in an attempt to stop Ziz's machinations from causing devastation and destruction, and this city is filled with tons of Case-53's and other desperate people stuck here. Aside from the defenses in place there isn't anything stopping you from leaving, but if its discovered that you "originated" from here, you will be incarcerated. Escalating (+2) this complication once will cause your entrance to be detected and recorded by the Protectorate in some manner. Doubling down (+4) on the first escalation will cause you to arrive during Simurgh's attack rather than at the start of canon. Worth TWO escalations. Maybe if you hurry, you'd be able to stop Noelle from turning into Echidna.

Note: +3 is not valid

objects.title: Being Taylor is Suffering
objects.text: Instead of choosing a new life, you wake up as Taylor Hebert in the hospital a few days after the locker incident. While before, reincarnating wouldn't have any negative effects, Taylor's life has left you with severe depression, trust issues, and in general a very damaged mental state. Your previous life memories combined with having your powers and perks will help, but you will still need time and effort to properly recover. Companions you have chosen will meet you at some point, and friends are still able to choose the nature of their new lives, with the exception that nothing can have had an impact on Taylor's life up to this point.

objects.title: You Needed Worthy Opponents
objects.text: Your presence and power here causes something to stir from dormancy. An Endbringer whose nature and abilities specifically are meant to oppose you emerges, and it will strike wherever doing so damages your cause and goals the most. It will appear within a year of the beginning of your adventure, announcing itself with a ferocious assault on your location. It might not even be alone, with every additional year seeing the emergence of another one. These Endbringers follow their own schedule of attack, and care nothing for whatever stands in the way of their targets. This complication can be taken up to TEN times, spawning up to TEN unique Endbringers per year to kill you. They will never be easy to defeat, and you cannot avoid these confrontations.

objects.title: The Slaughterhouse is Hiring
objects.text: Taking this complication means that Jack Slash himself will take an interest once you begin to make a name for yourself. The Slaughterhouse Nine will be headed your way, with you as its primary target. Jack will dedicate his time to seeing how he can break you, committing atrocities, slaughtering your loved ones and friends, cutting away everything positive in your life that he can reach. If you do not manage to resist them then you will either suffer a fate worse than death, or be broken and modified as a puppet and weapon by Bonesaw to further their grim ends. If you manage to drive them off you will have a reprieve, but only the death of Jack Slash will spell the end of his personal quest to peel you open and see what makes you tick.

objects.title: Sibling Rivalry
objects.text: You are not like other Endbringers and your siblings notice this. They will act to oppose you from ruining their strange designs, and will even attempt to slay you. They maintain their normal attack schedule, but when one strikes at a target, another will strike at you, using their powers to their fullest in an attempt to bring you down. This complication can be paired with "You Needed Worthy Opponents"

objects.title: Destructive Impulse
objects.text: By taking this complication you gain an unbelievably strong urge for conflict. Once every few months you will become overwhelmed by this urge, needing to participate in some significant conflict or destruction. This urge can be delayed temporarily, but can never be completely overcome, regardless of your willpower. This urge seeks to guide you to particular targets and locations, but you are capable of final control over how you vent your wrath. Freeing yourself would require finding the source and dealing with it. For some reason it feels close whenever the parahumans gather to fend you off. Almost like it was just within your reach.

objects.title: Golden Morning
objects.text:
Something about you registers as an anomaly, and whereas normally this would cause nothing but curiosity, by taking this complication it causes Scion to believe you are something to be eliminated. He will use his full power to eliminate you, and once he begins his hunt he will not stop until one of you is dead. At baseline (+2), this does not happen until he meets you in person, being completely unaware of you until your encounter. Escalating (+3) this complication will let him sense you and be on the lookout for your presence, even investigating anything that might bring him to you. Escalating again (+4) will bring him to full awareness immediately, causing him to hunt you down the moment your adventure begins. He will hound you and devastate anything that might so much as slow him down in his pursuit. You can hide from him for short periods, but he will always find you eventually.

Note: +1 isn't valid

objects.title: The Cycle Begins Anew
objects.text: At some point within a few years of your adventure, a second pair of entities arrives, scattering their Shards and beginning a second cycle. You will now have to face three entities, and one of them is lacking the mental blind spots that limit the Warrior entities. The fight for Earth Bet and all other Earths will be brutal and merciless, with only a miracle allowing you to prevent the eventually victorious entities from completing their evolutionary cycle and erasing Earth from every single alternate reality in the Wormverse.

rows.title: Victory?
rows.titleText:
So how exactly do you win and manage to get back home? Each origin has their own special little win condition beyond the primary, and completing it will allow you to return home whenever you like.

Primary: The universal win condition for everybody is to survive past the death of the remaining entity. You do not have to be the one to kill it, but your help would certainly make things go a lot smoother.

Self Insert: Self Inserts are capable of going back home after ten years have passed. This means it's possible to never have to deal with the entity if you play your cards right.

Reincarnation: Yours is easy, you just have to die. You live our a life here in Earth Bet, and when you pass away regardless of the circumstances you get to go home. Easy as going to sleep.

Endbringer: If you manage to slay the other Endbringers, or just eliminate them as a threat, you will be allowed to return home whenever you wish. You get a small plaque that declares you King of the Monsters, and Godzilla briefly appears to give you a congratulatory brofist before vanishing once more under the waves. Turns out he's a pretty chill guy who donates his movie proceeds to charity. Who knew?

You get your old body back, and no time has passed in your world while you were gone. If you were an Endbringer you are capable of switching between your two forms at will. You keep all powers and perks. The same applies to your friends, and if you wish then your other companions find themselves dropped onto your Earth, and will manage to find you within a month. You can open a portal to the Wormverse at any time, but from now on time passes normally and you'll have to explain any long absences.

defaultRowText: This is a row, and inside of it, you can place choices. On both rows and choices Requirements can be placed, which will block a row from being viewed, or make the player unable to select a choice, depending on either Point-types or the Ids of other choices. Point-types can be made in Features then Manage Points. Hovering over buttons will explain what they do. The Design of the project can be changed in 'Modify Design' at the side navigation bar, and private styling for each row can be turned on in the rows Settings. Default text like this can be turned off in Features -> Manage Defaults.
defaultChoiceText: This is a Choice, and inside of it, you can place images and text. Scores can be added to it, and have Point-types attached. Addons can be added underneath the image and text. In the Functions at the bottom of the choice, there is an array of different things that can be done. Default text like this can be turned off in Features then Manage Defaults.
